OUR STORY
Welcome to FLORIDA CRACKER
A place to feed your soul and belly at the same time. With a lifestyle driven by the roots of Old Florida, the Florida Cracker Culture takes you back to a simpler time in life where everyone is treated like family with true southern hospitality.
Brothers Blair & Ethan Hensley, born and raised in Brooksville, FL, are no strangers to the world of cooking. Coming from a family full of cooks, they have been in the kitchen for as long as they can remember.
Growing up, the brothers were fortunate enough to have their Granny Lewis live with them, regularly cooking 3 meals a day the old-fashioned way. With their mother Larie, known for her long-lasting restaurant “Mallie Kylas”, the boys both started working in the restaurant industry at a young age. It was only a matter of time before they ventured out on their own.

The term generally describes a class of early pioneers, mainly small farmers and cattle ranchers. Cracker cowboys are sometimes called cowhunters. When it was time for branding or driving the cattle to market, the cracker cowboys would search the swamps and round up all of the cows with the aid of whips and cattle dogs. They are also distinguishable by the style of their frontier homes, musical traditions, and foodways.
What is a Florida Cracker?
View The History Timeline
Chef Ethan Hensley
Ethan participated in the “Hernandough” Catering program in high school which influenced his passion early on. He later studied culinary at NECI and completed an internship in Nantucket, MA. Working in Nantucket at American Seasons,
Ethan was largely influenced and mentored by Chef Mike Lascola. He has been invited several times to the prestigious James Beard House to express his culinary skills with Chef Mike. He continued work for his mom in the off-season from Nantucket, but eventually decided to stay home to help with the family business and his pop for his final years.
Bus Boy Blair Hensley
Blair graduated from the University of West Alabama with a degree in Sports Medicine. During college, Blair had the opportunity to work for Ironman Triathlons traveling the country as the Logistics Coordinator. Later, he moved back home to help with the family businesses.
It wasn’t long before he acquired his first Hotdog Stand, Coney Island Drive-Inn, where he put his heart and soul into bringing the Brooksville staple back to life. After 8 years, he sold Coney Island and bought an old restaurant near downtown Brooksville, Farmer John’s. This finally allowed Blair and Ethan the opportunity to bring their dream restaurant to fruition and the “upside-down boot” that Blair had drawn on a napkin years ago was brought to life. In 2012 they opened the doors to Florida Cracker Kitchen and our brand has been growing ever since.

on
May 31, 2025
! This West Coast, all-women's tournament features a
Catch, Photo & Release
format for
Redfish, Trout, Snook, and Ladyfish
, with cash and prizes for winners.
Kick off the weekend at the
Gal's Gala and Captain/Angler meeting
on
Friday night
, with drinks, angler gifts, and plenty of fun. On
Saturday
, compete using the
iAngler Tournament app
to submit your catch photos, then celebrate at the
Awards Ceremony
.
Proceeds benefit
:
CCA Florida STAR Youth Scholarships
, providing $100,000 in annual scholarships for young anglers, including a $5,000 scholarship for a
Citrus County youth
.
Book, Line, & Thinkers
, an educational fishing program for
5th graders
offering hands-on learning experiences with support from the
Homosassa Guides Association
.
Register now
for a day of fishing, fun, and giving back!

OUR STORY
Welcome to FLORIDA CRACKER
A place to feed your soul and belly at the same time. With a lifestyle driven by the roots of Old Florida, the Florida Cracker Culture takes you back to a simpler time in life where everyone is treated like family with true southern hospitality.
Brothers Blair & Ethan Hensley, born and raised in Brooksville, FL, are no strangers to the world of cooking. Coming from a family full of cooks, they have been in the kitchen for as long as they can remember.
Growing up, the brothers were fortunate enough to have their Granny Lewis live with them, regularly cooking 3 meals a day the old-fashioned way. With their mother Larie, known for her long-lasting restaurant “Mallie Kylas”, the boys both started working in the restaurant industry at a young age. It was only a matter of time before they ventured out on their own.

OYSTER BAR & GRILL
The term generally describes a class of early pioneers, mainly small farmers and cattle ranchers. Cracker cowboys are sometimes called cowhunters. When it was time for branding or driving the cattle to market, the cracker cowboys would search the swamps and round up all of the cows with the aid of whips and cattle dogs. They are also distinguishable by the style of their frontier homes, musical traditions, and foodways.
What is a Florida Cracker?
View The History Timeline
Chef Ethan Hensley
Ethan participated in the “Hernandough” Catering program in high school which influenced his passion early on. He later studied culinary at NECI and completed an internship in Nantucket, MA. Working in Nantucket at American Seasons,
Ethan was largely influenced and mentored by Chef Mike Lascola. He has been invited several times to the prestigious James Beard House to express his culinary skills with Chef Mike. He continued work for his mom in the off-season from Nantucket, but eventually decided to stay home to help with the family business and his pop for his final years.
Bus Boy Blair Hensley
Blair graduated from the University of West Alabama with a degree in Sports Medicine. During college, Blair had the opportunity to work for Ironman Triathlons traveling the country as the Logistics Coordinator. Later, he moved back home to help with the family businesses.
It wasn’t long before he acquired his first Hotdog Stand, Coney Island Drive-Inn, where he put his heart and soul into bringing the Brooksville staple back to life. After 8 years, he sold Coney Island and bought an old restaurant near downtown Brooksville, Farmer John’s. This finally allowed Blair and Ethan the opportunity to bring their dream restaurant to fruition and the “upside-down boot” that Blair had drawn on a napkin years ago was brought to life. In 2012 they opened the doors to Florida Cracker Kitchen and our brand has been growing ever since.
